ğŸ” Problem Statement
Given a strictly sorted matrix of size n x m, where:

Each row is strictly increasing

The first element of each row is greater than the last element of the previous row
â†’ Check if a number x exists in the matrix.

ğŸ“Œ Matrix Properties
This is not just a row-wise sorted matrix. It has two important rules:

mat[i][j] < mat[i][j+1] (strict row-wise increase)

mat[i][0] > mat[i-1][m-1] (strict inter-row increase)

âœ… So, the matrix can be flattened into a 1D sorted array
Example:
Matrix:
[ [ 1,  5,  9],
  [14, 20, 21],
  [30, 34, 43] ]

Flattened:
[1, 5, 9, 14, 20, 21, 30, 34, 43]
âœ… Optimal Approach: 1D Binary Search
ğŸ”¸ Logic:
Consider 1D index mid between 0 to n*m - 1

Convert 1D index to 2D:

row = mid / m

col = mid % m

Compare mat[row][col] with x

âœ… Java Code:
class Solution {
    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] mat, int x) {
        int n = mat.length;
        int m = mat[0].length;

        int low = 0, high = n * m - 1;

        while (low <= high) {
            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
            int midElement = mat[mid / m][mid % m];

            if (midElement == x) return true;
            else if (midElement < x) low = mid + 1;
            else high = mid - 1;
        }

        return false;
    }
}
â±ï¸ Time and Space Complexity
Metric	Value
Time	O(log(n Ã— m))
Space	O(1)

ğŸ§  Why Not Use Staircase Search?
Staircase search works when:

Each row is sorted â•

Each column is also sorted â•

âŒ Here, columns arenâ€™t necessarily sorted.
âœ… Better to use 1D binary search due to strict ordering.

ğŸ§ª Example Dry Run
Input:
mat = [[1, 5, 9], [14, 20, 21], [30, 34, 43]], x = 20

Step	mid	mat[mid/m][mid%m]	Comparison
1	4	20	âœ… Found

âš ï¸ Common Mistakes
Mistake	Fix
Using mat[mid][mid]	Must map 1D to 2D properly: mat[mid / m][mid % m]
Using row-wise binary search	Slower â€“ takes O(n * log m) time
Confusing this with column-sorted matrix	They're different!

ğŸ“Œ Summary Table
Matrix Type	Best Approach	Time Complexity
Row-wise sorted only	Binary search per row	O(n Ã— log m)
Row + column sorted	Staircase search	O(n + m)
Strictly sorted (Leetcode-74)	Flattened binary search	O(log(n Ã— m))
